# Compute Engine ‚Äî Cursor Rules

## Project Overview

A math compute engine built from scratch. Every algorithm is hand-implemented in C++23 with optional CUDA acceleration and Python bindings via nanobind. Two goals: a real HPC library AND a LinkedIn content series (3‚Äì4 posts/week, one function/topic per post).

## Stack

- **C++23** ‚Äî core language. Use `std::expected`, `std::mdspan`, `std::span`, `std::print`.
- **CUDA** ‚Äî optional GPU acceleration, toggled via `COMPUTE_ENABLE_CUDA=ON`. SM 86 target (RTX 3060).
- **nanobind** ‚Äî Python bindings. Zero-copy numpy arrays via `nb::ndarray`.
- **CMake 4.3 + Ninja** ‚Äî build system. Presets: `debug`, `relwithdebinfo`, `release`, `release-cuda`.
- **OneTBB** ‚Äî CPU parallelism (prefer over OpenMP).
- **FFTW3** ‚Äî CPU FFT (available via system install).
- **Catch2** ‚Äî unit tests. **Google Benchmark** ‚Äî performance tests.

## Non-Negotiable Rules

1. **No math libraries in the engine.** Eigen and Boost.Math are on the system but are only used in `tests/` as oracles. Never `#include` them in `include/` or `src/`.

2. **CUDA is always optional.** Every GPU function needs a CPU fallback. `COMPUTE_ENABLE_CUDA=OFF` must build cleanly with all tests passing.

3. **No CUDA types in public headers.** `cudaStream_t`, `float4*`, `dim3`, etc. stay in `.cu` files and the dispatch layer. `include/compute/` is pure C++.

4. **Error handling via `std::expected`.** Use `compute::core::Result<T>` in C++ code. Convert to Python exceptions only at the nanobind boundary in `bindings/python/`.

5. **Implement everything from scratch.** No GSL, no Armadillo, no OpenBLAS as a dependency. The point is to build it.

6. **GPU kernels live in real shader/source files.** Metal kernels (MSL) go in a `.metal` file ‚Äî never embedded as a C++ string literal. Likewise CUDA kernels in `.cu` and Vulkan kernels in `.comp`. When a kernel compiler is unavailable (e.g. the Metal Toolchain), embed the `.metal` file into a generated header at build time (CMake `file(READ)` + `configure_file`) and compile at runtime via `newLibraryWithSource:` ‚Äî the `.metal` file stays the single source of truth, never a hand-written string.

## Directory Structure

```
include/compute/        ‚Üê public API headers (pure C++, no CUDA types)
  core/                 ‚Üê aligned_buffer, simd_traits, error.hpp, compute_policy
  linalg/               ‚Üê matrix types, decompositions, iterative solvers
  numerical/            ‚Üê root-finding, interpolation, quadrature, FFT, autodiff
  ode/                  ‚Üê ODE integrators
  stats/                ‚Üê statistics
  probability/          ‚Üê distributions, sampling, MCMC
  combinatorics/        ‚Üê combinatorial algorithms, DSA

src/compute/            ‚Üê compiled .cpp units (mirrors include/)
  cuda/                 ‚Üê .cu GPU kernels (linalg/, numerical/, stats/)

bindings/python/        ‚Üê nanobind modules (_compute_<module>.cpp per module)
tests/unit/             ‚Üê Catch2 tests (test_<module>.cpp)
tests/bench/            ‚Üê Google Benchmark (bench_<module>.cpp)
scripts/python/         ‚Üê Python demo scripts and notebooks
docs/weekly/            ‚Üê LinkedIn post drafts
cmake/                  ‚Üê CompilerOptions.cmake, CUDAConfig.cmake, PythonBindings.cmake
```

## Namespaces

```cpp
compute::core       // buffer, SIMD traits, error types, dispatch policy
compute::linalg     // all linear algebra
compute::num        // numerical analysis
compute::ode        // ODE solvers
compute::stats      // statistics
compute::prob       // probability
compute::comb       // combinatorics
compute::cuda       // GPU paths (only included when CUDA is enabled)
```

## CPU/GPU Dispatch Pattern

Every function with a GPU path follows this pattern:

```cpp
// In include/compute/linalg/gemm.hpp (pure C++, no CUDA types)
namespace compute::linalg {
    Result<void> gemm(std::span<const double> A,
                      std::span<const double> B,
                      std::span<double>       C,
                      std::size_t m, std::size_t n, std::size_t k);
}

// In src/compute/linalg/gemm.cpp ‚Äî checks ComputePolicy, routes to CPU or GPU
// In src/compute/cuda/linalg/gemm_kernels.cu ‚Äî GPU implementation
```

The `compute::core::ComputePolicy` thread-local (`cpu_only` / `gpu_preferred` / `automatic`) controls routing. Check `core::get_policy()` in the dispatch layer.

## Code Style

- **No comments explaining what code does.** Good names do that.
- **Comments only for WHY** something non-obvious is done: numerical stability choices, alignment requirements, cache tiling rationale, workarounds for specific hardware behavior.
- **No docstrings. No multi-line comment blocks.**
- Tolerances in tests come from the algorithm's theoretical error bound, not arbitrary constants.
- Prefer `std::size_t` for sizes/indices. Use `ptrdiff_t` for signed differences.
- Column-major storage for matrices (cache-friendly for column operations in decompositions).

## Build

```bash
cmake --preset relwithdebinfo          # configure
cmake --build build/relwithdebinfo -j  # build
cd build/relwithdebinfo && ctest       # test

cmake --preset release-cuda            # CUDA build (Week 4+)
```

